fields: From relaxed to contracted the length of the A band {{c1::does not change}}

T tubules are {{c1::invaginations of the plasma membrane}}
Sarcoplasmic reticulum is {{c1::ER in skeletal muscles}} and has a primary fuction of {{c1::[Ca] management}}
Terminal cisterna are {{c1::dilated portions of the SR}}
Triad contract between {{c1::a t tubule and two terminal cisternae}}
Order of events in stimulation of muscle contraction is:

1-Ach released from axon -> binds to receptors in sarcolemma
2-Action potential generated down T tubule
3-Ca released from SR (voltage triggered)
4-Ca binds to troponin, myosin-actin cross-bridges form
5-Ach-esterase removes ach from cleft
6-Ca back to SR
7-Tropomyosin binds active sites -> cross-bridges detach
(AACCACT)

1-Binding site on actin available
2-Hydrolysis and departure of ADP + P causes flexing of cross bridge
3-Binding of new ATP uncouples cross bridge
4-Hydrolysis of ATP reenergizes the bridge
Rigor mortis caused by {{c1::inability of cells to prevent Ca entry}} causing permanent contraction due to {{c1::myosin binding to actin}}
Muscle rigor ends once proteins are destroyed by autolysis
The stretch receptors in muscles are {{c1::muscle spindles}}
Knee reflex test causes stretch of {{c1::spindle fibers}} which causes {{c1::APs to the spinal cord}} resulting in {{c1::contraction to resist stretch}}
Sensory neurons in the spinal cord synapse directly with {{c1::alpha motor neurson}}
